div.div: Scattered bones atop 15743-- not really a cluster. The hand-picked collection is interesting, but debatably representative of a single deposit. Large bones, from multiple taxa: cattle (ca. 40%) and caprines (ca. 55%), plus equid (3 bones), pig (2). Equids are represented by two teeth and a foot bone; pig by two teeth; cattle by cranial remains, a phalanx, and long bone splinters; caprines by all parts of the body (horn core, teeth and jaws, long bones (mostly shafts), ribs, a few vertebrae, one astragalus and one phalanx (ie, feet and small bones are scarce)). One, perhaps two, of the caprine bones are large goat bones, and there are also two large pieces of goat horn. A high proportion of jaws & teeth, in contrast to possibly-associated 17094. No clear focus on either meaty or symbolically-prominent bones, although the taxonomic distribution is unusual. No burning, surface conditions lightly weathered, and a fairly fragile atlas is complete: many of the bones were quickly covered and not underfoot. However, there are two gnawed pieces, and a minority of the bones are more moderately weathered. Maybe the majority of the unit represents a dump, but not of a single episode of activity. (A minority are pretty clearly bones from the middens either below or above.) It is at least as plausible that the bones represent a coincidental accumulation of large bones near a midden interface layer, or what happens if you just pick up the biggest, prettiest bones visible. No flotation taken.

arch:string.div: The unique identifier for each contextual unit, matching those used in the central Çatalhöyük excavation database and in publications. The excavation uses single-context recording.
